Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: While the original HyperDisco-Adapter idea is highly innovative—leveraging disentangled hypernetworks for zero-shot adaptation—it still assumes access to structured metadata (e.g., domain tags, WALS features) at inference time. In real-world deployment, such metadata may be noisy, missing, or expensive to curate. My intuition is that true scalability requires *self-supervised discovery* of both domain and language characteristics directly from raw input text, eliminating reliance on external annotations. Furthermore, existing methods like m4 Adapter and DA-Net rely on either pre-defined language codes or shared encoders that entangle linguistic and stylistic information. I propose a shift: instead of feeding explicit typological or domain labels into a hypernetwork, we design a **self-monitoring meta-adapter** that *infers* disentangled control vectors from input representations using contrastive meta-clustering. This enables fully unsupervised zero-shot generalization—even when neither domain nor target language was observed during training. The key novelty lies in replacing hand-engineered inputs with emergent, self-organized latent factors via a dual-contrastive mechanism: one branch learns domain-invariant style prototypes across languages, while another learns language-invariant structural archetypes across domains. These are then composed via a lightweight hypernetwork to modulate adapter weights. Crucially, this removes dependency on external databases (like WALS), enhances robustness in low-resource settings, and enables plug-and-play adaptation from raw text alone. Unlike Paper 2—which uses unlabeled data for projection but still requires known target languages—our method discovers language identity implicitly. Compared to DA-Net’s multi-source setup, we focus on single-source-to-arbitrary-target generalization without any fine-tuning. This idea pushes parameter-efficient adaptation toward true autonomy in dynamic environments.

